Agricultural speculation
German bank leaves commodity business by lights
Christian Teevs
Deutsche Bank is on their business with agricultural commodities?
After SPIEGEL-ONLINE information Josef Ackermann asked a working group to examine the impact of speculation for the poor of the world.
In January, the company chief want to draw conclusions.
Hamburg -
The matter is clear for the German citizens: 84 percent of Germans think it is not acceptable, according to a study that banks with agricultural commodities such as wheat or corn.
Two-thirds of the respondents even demand that the Deutsche Bank and other lenders from this business, because it exacerbates the problems of the poorest in the world.
This is the result of a Forsa survey commissioned by the consumer organisation Foodwatch.
The study is based on a report that Foodwatch presented in mid-October.
The author shows Harald Schumann that bets on global stock exchanges, commodity prices - and the banks are therefore an accessory on global hunger problem.
The campaign of consumer protector is directed specifically against Deutsche Bank chief Josef Ackermann, even if big banks like Goldman Sachs or Morgan Stanley.
Commodity bets were originally intended for traders against price fluctuations.
But most experts agree that the gamblers have decoupled from supply and demand - and make profits at the expense of the poorest.
Unlike the US competitors reacted Ackermann to the criticism: he promised to investigate the allegations and said that no business it is "worth the good name of the Deutsche Bank to gamble."
According to the information provided by SPIEGEL ONLINE an International Labour is currently examining the allegations from the Foodwatch Report.
The review to be completed by the end of the year, then the results will be presented to the board of Deutsche Bank, with a recommendation on how this should be handled.
At the end of January, the then head of the bank say what consequences.
In the end, could be a reduction in the commodity business, or even the complete departure.
Ackermann fusses over his image
Foodwatch chief Thilo Bode welcomed the news, but at the same time, his criticism of the financial industry: "betting on rising food prices illustrates dramatically as reckless banks of the public."
Ackermann stand as a top bank lobbyist now, particularly in the duty.
"The Deutsche Bank must remove all plants from its portfolio, where money will be used to take bets on food prices," said Bode.
"Regardless of whether it is Mr Ackermann hunger suffering people or the reputation of the Deutsche Bank."
The understanding of Ackermann is surprising at first glance, but it is clear that the company chief a few months before his departure from office would make a perfect picture.
On Monday, the Deutsche Bank announced that the CEO differently than planned, will not change in the board.
With a move away from the controversial agricultural speculation he could be pumping up his image.
And possible losses he needs very little to do - after all, could have his successor.
Every second would terminate commodity assets
Foodwatch trying to keep the pressure on the manager.
So far, more than 30000 Internet users in the campaign of the organisation.
On Tuesday, Bode published the poll, for which the institute Forsa 1001 people interviewed on 7 and 8 November.
Just 11 percent think it is legitimate that the Deutsche Bank facilities, where bets on food prices.
Many bank customers would also be personal consequences when they learn that their bank involved in such transactions: half of the poll, according to terminate all installations where money is flowing into commodity speculation.
43% would advise acquaintances of such a bank to cancel 49% to reflect their accounts and to switch to another institution.
21er house in Vienna
The relocated pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with highs, lows and happy endings: the Austrian World Expo pavilion from Brussels in 1958, won prizes in Vienna museum was empty and descended.
Now, he will be re-opened as an exhibition.
If dreams of modern postwar architecture, clear forms, glass halls, courageous swings and new building materials, which are typical for the belief in the technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion of Karl Schwanzer architects for the Brussels World Expo in 1958, a striking and famous example.
Tail pavilion at the Grand Prix d ' Architecture for his easy and pending operates steel-glass design.
The building is now a landmark contemporary architecture.
He made the architects know that Austria at the next World Expo pavilion built.
It was 1973, finally internationally famous with his legendary BMW Vierzylinderhaus plus schüsselartigem side in Munich.
His planned as a temporary exhibition pavilion had converted one of the world exhibition at the Swiss garden at the Vienna Südbahnhof, and in 1962, it opened a museum of the 20th century - the 1920s house it was called.
It was likely the building but neither physically and technically as a museum - no walls on the slopes of the art, not a good climate.
Nevertheless, it has been used for so long, until the contemporary art in Vienna, a new house.
Since 2001, the building was empty and more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz converted the pavilion, he now says, "21er House" and will be used as a museum of contemporary art in the future.
Tuesday evening, the museum opened Belvedere, the house is the first exhibition - a stroke of luck in all respects.
Through the restart Agnes Husslein-Arco, in 2007, the new director of the Austrian gallery Belvedere.
Husslein-Arco, holders of art historian with considerable career in the youth as Eiskunstläufererin later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and a founding director of the Museum of modernity Salzburg, converting strongly among politicians and conservationists monument, they acquired public funds and private sponsors ' money and use.
Should contemporary art works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba issued by the eponymous foundation, there should be a cafe and a bookshop, and an office house had to be built.
Strict supervision, small budget
The implementation was Krischanitz the ideal occupation.
Not only because of its sensitive converted Joseph Olbrichs Secession in Vienna and expanded and won the competition, but because he has studied in Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion for him was an "incredibly important place" where he was "almost every weekend" exhibitions.
He knew the Ur-draft, and he knew the problems of the building, which is already in its transfer to Vienna and lost his Umnutzung of generosity and lightness.
The current renovation, there were far greater problems: the building was "a Energieschleuder," says Krischanitz.
The windows profiles of the glass facade have changed, enhanced fiber glass insulation and the glass roof replaced by special security glass.
Bridges cold steel makers have been strengthened or replaced, and asbestos-filled blankets have been refurbished.
Two -got room for the new use, a reduced light gap between house and road for Belichtung, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the easy Schwanzer pavilion.
The original external doors are removed, the house is in the old rotbraunen rust protection Farbton.
And the cinema is even exactly as it was before.
And all this under the strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found, that is a good thing, and it is cheap and Denkmalschutzamt liked," says Krischanitz and highlights an abrasive ground in -.
Despite all the constraints, problems and improvements to the building is flexible and easy.
It is been difficult with the pavilion, " daherkam from Brussels, " said Krischanitz recently, a typical ' Drop-in-the-City history. "
So an architecture "always in the wrong place," and still wants to "create a real awareness."
In this case, the 21er house, however, is not entered in the wrong place, because it is an urban fluke: around the Swiss garden is just completely planned ' Central Station Quartier ' office and residential buildings.
And another fluke may still happen: the 21er households could get reinforcement from another Krischanitz construction, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg has bought the Berlin Temporäre art hall, and we hear that it is negotiating with the city a neighbourly location within the Swiss garden.
