7 lessons of interviews with the late Steve Jobs, which was shown this week in a theatre
After the death of Steve Jobs on 5 October, compared to some with Henry Ford and stressed the technology genius as a great modern inventors.
What Apple fans, but perhaps most revealing in the recently discovered Jobs interview, which this week dusted off special film displays on the major markets, is to understand how this creative head of business processes and procedures.
He was certainly a designer, a dreamer and self-styled Hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer eager to tinker diagram - a man who believed that many business leaders, " a disease of thought, " a really great idea accounts for 90 percent of the work... [but] there is an enormous amount of craft art between a great idea and a great product. "
In 1995, developed Bob Cringely led the TV series " triumph of the specialist idiots ' on the departure of the personal computer, and he sat for more than an hour with Jobs, in a rare, detailed talks.
At this point in time were relegated 10 years have passed since Jobs from Apple was, and he worked hard on his new computer company NeXT, and was on the broad adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of Cringleys interview was used in specialist idiots, he says that the Kopiervorlagen of interviews in the delivery.
After Jobs death discovered a full VHS-copy in the garage of the director.
