Climatic adversity blocking the economy
In the first year, in which Mario López Valdez is in the government, rose in Sinaloa, unemployment and undeclared work, while the foreign investment and the economy stagnated.
In 2011, will remain in the economic history of the Sinaloas in memory, and it is the first year, Mario López Valdez, who described himself as the initiator of change and fueled great hopes on the economic growth, the government is, however, as a result of the climatic odds of growth is not deteriorating, but on the contrary, the most important economic indicators.
The low temperatures in February caused not only losses in millions of dollars in agriculture, but also stuck to the growth of the state economy close borders and caused in the first quarter of the year with a general decline in economic activity by 3.6% This is mainly on the historic reduction of agricultural development 31.16 percent, slowing to other sectors of the economy.
According to the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo were Rural Sustentable. Mexican Council for sustainable agricultural development) report on the impact of the Frosts were 582000 hectare of land damaged, 78.03 per cent complete, and the remaining 21.07% partially destroyed were affected mainly the cultivation of vegetables, maize and chickpeas.
The decline in economic activity until November has increased steadily in the Mexican state unemployment; the Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed in the first quarter of the year, a rapid rise in unemployment, from January to March 55053 inhabitants had no Sinaloas employment, which rose 4.53 per cent of the working population in the second quarter, the unemployment rate to 5.28% from July to September to 6.19 percent, 74000 unemployed in Sinaloa. The 18969 persons are more than in the first quarter of the year.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa in the year to several factors: the economist Gerardo López Cervantes, dean of the School of Economic and Social Sciences University Autónoma (UAS), commented on the policy of public institutions indirectly declare the growing unemployment.
"What we are witnessing is a rise in unemployment, which was adopted with several factors that has to do partly with cash losses in the market as a result of the cuts through legislation to combat money laundering in Congress, because those who illicitly accumulate dollars to invest, it is not easy for them to work, or to use for anything else," he said.
Stopped migration
López Cervantes has pointed out that the increase in unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people is the country in search of work abroad, especially in the United States, left, and this is due to the entry of problems and, on the other hand, because it is difficult to find work, and these people are here to stay and look for work, unemployment," he says.
Undeclared work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious, if one takes into account the high proportion of undeclared work incorporates under INEGI 60.38% of the country's employees, who work without paying into the coffers of the social insurance.
Unemployment and moonlighting low wages, the lowest in Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican social security) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (governmental authority for labour and social welfare in Mexico).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa until September 5352 pesos; that is much less than the total state average of 7375 pesos.
Decline in FDI
In addition to the reduction of economic activity and rising unemployment is the sharpest decline in foreign direct investment (FDI) in the last ten years, according to Secretaría de Economía (state authority), FDI from January to June 630597 dollars, a loss of 87.74% compared to the 5143 312 dollars in the same period in the previous year in 2011.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (government agency for economic development) recorded an overall investment in 17280000 pesos in 2011, above all, the companies comes from the tertiary sector.
The debt
In the face of the economic crisis, the country's government in July, the National Congress, a loan of 3000000000 pesos, which should be invested to kickstart the economy in infrastructure projects in the 18 communities and the country's Congress approved an amount of 200600000 pesos, however, could be made until November, no positive effects of the debt to any of the economic sectors in the country.
Reactions
For the representatives of entrepreneurship, the first year of government, Mario López Valdés governmental incompetence.
Miguel Loredo López, chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (state chamber of manufacturing in Mexico), argued that no efforts to harmonize the views of different sectors, including the country's government, have been made in 2011.
"Economic activity in Sinaloa this year was very poor and it needs to be worked hard to regain lost ground this year and 2012, we must make the effort to double the efforts of all, and in particular the progress of the already well entered government voted teams are not sufficiently aligned," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events such as the frost at the start of the year, the economic development of the country difficult and slow.
"The economic flow is the result of a number of events, including the Frosts is one of the most important effects of a slower economy, which is not enough in a dynamic economy, which could produce a reasonable flow of processes, products and services, and that is why we will finish the year well below our expectations," he said.
Redefine appeal
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Mexico) employers ' association in Sinaloa declared that we must make the state more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that it was working, and we believe that there is a long-term programme to redefine the economic appeal and to develop the country, because it is important that all the material and human resources to activate Sinaloas," he said.
There is much to be done
The chairman of Coparmex stressed how important it is to develop a future in which the efforts of the government in better roads.
"In general, I would say that the government in various fields has achieved good results, and the economic development is progressing, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current government is making progress made with the government.
"There are areas in which we can say that the government has comprehensively acted what I can say is that it was working and that the government is aware that a lot of work lies ahead," he said.
